			<introduction>
				<p>
					You are manufacturing custom dinner plates. The total cost of manufacturing two items is $6, and the total cost of manufacturing four items is $11. The cost per item is constant.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Write down a formula for the total cost <m>C(x)</m> as a function of the number of items <m>x</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						Because the <em>cost per item</em> is constant, the <em>total cost</em> function is linear.   
					</p>
					<p>
						We must therefore use the point slope form of the line 
						<me>
							C(x) = m (x-x_1) + y_1	
						</me>
						The knowledge that <m>2</m> items corresponds to a cost of <m>6</m> dollars tells us that the point <m>x_1=2</m> and <m>y_1=6</m> is on our line.
					</p>
					<p>
						We are also told that <m>x_2=4</m> items corresponds to a price of <m>y_2=11</m> dollars, giving us the second point on our line. 
					</p>
					<p>
						To find <m>m</m>, use the slope formula <m>m = \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \dfrac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} = \dfrac{11-6}{4-2}=\dfrac{5}{2}=2.5</m>
					</p>
					<p>
						In other words, the slope is <m>m=\dfrac{2.5 \text{ \$}}{1\text{ item}}</m>, or 2.5 $ per item.
					</p>
					<p>
						Putting it all together, we get the equation 
						<me>
							C(x) = 2.5 (x - 2) + 6
						</me>
						or equivalently
						<m> C(x) = 2.5 (x - 4) + 11</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
